        <h2 id="examples">Real ephemeral content examples</h2>
        <p>Two concrete cases showing how ephemeral content produces measurable business results.</p>

        <h3>1. Local coffee shop — daily drink of the day</h3>
        <p>A local coffee shop posts daily Instagram Stories featuring the "drink of the day" with a countdown sticker (resetting each day at open). Average Story views: 800 — exceeding feed post reach. The countdown sticker creates a daily ritual: regular customers check Stories every morning to see the special. The format runs with a phone camera and takes under 5 minutes to produce.</p>

        <h3>2. SaaS company — weekly tips archived to Highlights</h3>
        <p>A SaaS company shares weekly product tips via Stories: short screen recordings showing one feature per frame. After 24 hours, each tip is pinned to a "Tips" Highlight collection. New followers discover the Highlight, get 6 months of product training in one browsing session, and convert at a higher rate. The ephemeral format generates initial engagement; the Highlight converts the long tail.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Ephemeral content vs. evergreen content — when to use each</h2>
        <p>Both serve a content strategy, but at different points in the customer journey and with different production economics.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use ephemeral content for</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Daily brand touchpoints without feed clutter</li>
              <li>Flash sales and limited-time offers</li>
              <li>Behind-the-scenes authenticity</li>
              <li>Polls and audience research</li>
              <li>Event coverage in real time</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use evergreen content for</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>SEO traffic that compounds over months</li>
              <li>Permanent product education</li>
              <li>Long-form how-to guides</li>
              <li>Content that earns backlinks over time</li>
              <li>Glossary and resource pages</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for ephemeral content</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Post 3-7 frames per session.</strong> The optimal Instagram Stories cadence for most brands is 3-7 frames daily. Under 3 and you're not filling the slot; over 10 and you start losing viewers mid-sequence.</li>
          <li><strong>Lead with the hook.</strong> The first frame determines whether someone taps through or skips. Your strongest visual or most provocative question goes first.</li>
          <li><strong>Use interactive stickers every time.</strong> Polls, questions, quizzes, and countdowns generate engagement signals that the algorithm amplifies. Static Stories perform consistently lower than interactive ones.</li>
          <li><strong>Include a link sticker on commercial content.</strong> Instagram link stickers are available to all accounts. Every Story promoting a product, blog post, or offer should include one.</li>
          <li><strong>Archive valuable Stories to Highlights.</strong> Organize Highlights by theme: Products, Reviews, Tips, Events. New followers use Highlights as their first research stop on your profile.</li>
          <li><strong>Maintain a consistent visual template.</strong> Brand colors, fonts, and logo placement in Story frames build visual recognition across hundreds of posts. Canva templates reduce per-Story production time to under 2 minutes.</li>
          <li><strong>Respond to Story replies in DMs.</strong> When viewers respond to polls or send messages from Stories, they become high-intent contacts. A direct reply converts at dramatically higher rates than broadcast content.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — treating Stories as a broadcast channel</div>
          <p>Brands that repurpose feed posts directly into Stories see low engagement. Stories audiences expect raw, real-time content — not polished graphics resized from a post. The most effective Stories feel unplanned even when they're not. Production quality works against you in the Stories context.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common ephemeral content mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Posting only when you have "something to say"</strong> — inconsistent Stories cadence drops you out of the habit loop your followers build around daily viewing.</li>
          <li><strong>No interactive elements</strong> — static image Stories without polls or stickers generate no algorithm signal and reach only your existing followers.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping Highlights</strong> — valuable product or FAQ content that expires after 24 hours is wasted. Archive to Highlights for permanent access.</li>
          <li><strong>Repurposing feed posts without reformatting</strong> — feed post dimensions (1:1 or 4:5) leave large blank areas in Stories (9:16). Always reframe content for the vertical format.</li>
          <li><strong>No link sticker on commercial content</strong> — if you're promoting a product or offer without a link, you're asking viewers to take an extra step that most won't take.</li>
        </ul>

